WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:15.624
Up to now we've analyzed one setup at a time. But real
traders don't run just one, they run several. This lab
answers the question that comes next. Which ones should I
run together, and what actually happens when I do?

2
00:00:16.224 --> 00:00:31.920
It's the Compare and Combine lab, in Step three. The big
idea is this. It nets multiple moves together, day by day,
in real dollars. Not percentages, dollars. So it can
safely add a Nasdaq trade to a gold trade, something raw
percentages could never do.

3
00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:50.280
You build two baskets, Set A and Set B. Tick any moves or
assets into each one. Then the lab plays them out side by
side and shows you the difference. Is A better than B? And
what if you simply traded both? Each set can even use its
own attempt filter, so you can pit first attempts against
second attempts.

4
00:00:50.880 --> 00:01:09.552
Two numbers tell the story here. Win Rate in days is the
share of trading days the combined basket finished green,
because when you run several setups at once, what matters
is the day's net, not each single trade. And Max Drawdown
is the deepest the combined equity ever fell from its
high. That is your real risk when you stack setups
together.

5
00:01:10.152 --> 00:01:25.944
And you don't have to guess the combination. The
recommended baskets pick which moves to pair for you. By
Kelly sizing for raw growth, by minimum variance for the
smoothest ride, by maximum Sharpe for balance, or by pure
diversification. One click sends that basket straight into
your other tools.

6
00:01:26.544 --> 00:01:37.680
This is the very first step from a single edge to a real
portfolio. Two mediocre setups that don't lose on the same
days can be far safer, and far steadier, than one great
setup all by itself.

7
00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:41.520
Don't just find an edge. Find edges that fit together.
